{
  "doc_id": "34866",
  "text": "The single-variant analysis provided evidence for 2 additional potential candidate genes: ANK2 (ankyrin 2) and TRPC3 (transient receptor potential cation channel). ANK2 is a member of the ankyrin family of proteins and is required for the targeting and stability of the Na + /Ca 2+ exchanger in cardiomyocytes. Mutations in this gene lead to long-QT syndrome and cardiac arrhythmia [CITATION_1] . ANK2 has been located in a 1-lod support interval linked to resting heart rate [CITATION_2] . TRPC3 is a renal Ca 2+ channel, expressed in principal cells of the collecting duct. The expression levels of TRPC3 have been associated with systolic hypertension in humans [CITATION_3] and are higher in spontaneously hypertensive rats than in normotensive Wistar-Kyoto rats [CITATION_4] .",
